For Immediate Release
February 21, 2006

For more information, contact:
Alison Buckholtz, alison@arl.org



RAY ENGLISH ELECTED SPARC STEERING COMMITTEE CHAIR

Oberlin=92s English Recently Named 2006 ACRL Librarian of the Year

Washington, DC =96 The SPARC Steering Committee,=20
whose newest members began their three-year terms=20
on January 1, has elected Ray English to the=20
position of Chair.  English, the Azariah Smith=20
Root Director of Libraries at Oberlin College,=20
has served as a SPARC Steering Committee member since 1999.

English was recently named the 2006 Association=20
of College and Research Libraries=92 (ACRL)=20
Academic/Research Librarian of the Year, an award=20
that recognizes an outstanding member of the=20
library profession who has made a significant=20
national or international contribution to=20
academic/research librarianship and library development.

=93SPARC is a dynamic, forward-focused and=20
fast-paced organization that I have greatly=20
enjoyed working with since its founding, and I am=20
pleased that I will have the opportunity as Chair=20
to contribute to its important work in the=20
scholarly communication marketplace,=94 English said.

=93Ray English is an original thinker who brings=20
creativity and tactical leadership to the=20
position of SPARC Chair,=94 said Heather Joseph,=20
SPARC=92s Executive Director.  =93Our steering=20
committee and I believe he will help move forward=20
several important changes to benefit libraries, librarians, and=
 researchers.=94

SPARC's voting membership, which includes=20
representatives from over 150 academic libraries=20
in the U.S. and Canada, also elected the=20
following individuals to serve on the SPARC=20
Steering Committee for three-year terms which began January 1:

=95    Larry Alford, Temple University
=95    Sherrie Bergman, Bowdoin College (by re-election)
=95    Ray English, Oberlin College (by re-election)
=95    Diane Graves, Trinity University
=95    John Ober, University of California
=95    Sarah Pritchard, University of California, Santa Barbara

The new members join the current members of the SPARC Steering Committee:

=95    Nancy Baker, University of Iowa
=95    Deb Carver, University of Oregon
=95    Gwendolyn Ebbett, University of Windsor
=95    Joyce Ogburn, University of Utah
=95    Carolyne Presser, University of Manitoba
=95    Bas Savenije, University of Utrecht

Steering Committee members whose terms concluded=20
in December include outgoing Chair Jim Neal=20
(Columbia University), Sam Demas (Carleton=20
College), Sarah Michalak (UNC Chapel Hill), and=20
MacKenzie Smith (MIT). Neal=92s service to the=20
steering committee was recognized with a plaque=20
and a speech from SPARC Executive Director=20
Heather Joseph at the ALA Midwinter Meeting in San Antonio.

The SPARC Nominating Committee for this year's=20
election included Shirley Baker, Charles Lowry, and Pamela Snelson.

***

SPARC
SPARC (Scholarly Publishing and Academic=20
Resources Coalition) and SPARC Europe are an=20
international alliance of more than 300 academic=20
and research libraries working to correct=20
imbalances in the scholarly publishing=20
system.  SPARC=92s advocacy, educational, and=20
publisher partnership programs encourage expanded=20
dissemination of research. SPARC is located on=20
the Web at=20
<http://www.arl.org/sparc;>http://www.arl.org/sparc; SPARC Europe is at
<http://www.sparceurope.org>http://www.sparceurope.org.



________________
Alison Buckholtz
SPARC Consultant
alison@arl.org
phone: 202 251 7845

